td.paragraph: PRESUMPTIVE PANEL:

New Patient No Opioid Risk Category Assigned. Each patient will be assigned to an opioid risk category based on their medical history, compliance with medical therapy, history of aberrant behavior, toxicology screen results, SOAPP-R scores, FL Prescription Drug Monitoring Program database results, as well as the discretion of their treating physician; the opioid risk category will dictate how compliance monitoring each patient will require, the elements of the screening tests and approximately how often they will undergo toxicology screens although additional or less frequent testing may be justified and performed at the discretion of the treating provider when unforeseen circumstances arise. A patient's opioid risk category may be changed in the future at the discretion of the treating provider based on improvement or deterioration in the variables described above that are used to determine the risk category. Aberrant behavior includes but is not limited to the following: 1) misusing, abusing and/or developing an addiction to opioids, controlled substances and illicit drugs; 2) non-compliance with medical therapy; 3) obtaining pain medications from other medical providers or individuals and/or using outdated prescriptions; and 4) diversion of prescribed medications.

a. Red risk level patients are those whose findings on risk assessment (see above) indicate the highest relative likelihood of aberrant drug-related behavior, and those patients using or prescribed opioids, benzodiazepines, TCA'S, Neuroleptics and sleep inducing medications, which can each enhance and synergistically increase the therapeutic blood level desired, including the use, misuse, and/or abuse of prescribed medications, non-prescribed medications and/or illicit controlled substances, and a higher likelihood of diversion.

b. Yellow risk level patients are those whose assessment findings indicate a reasonable likelihood of aberrant drug-related behavior and the possible usage of opioid medications and similar medicines used in the "RED" category also. Yellow patients may include those who might have been categorized as Red patients in the past, but whose clinical history has reduced the level of risk associated with treatment. Yellow patients may also include those who might have been categorized as Green, but whose risk stratification causes the provider to believe the risk of treating is higher than Green, but not to the level of Red.

c. Green patients are those whose assessment findings indicate a low likelihood of aberrant drug-related behavior and possibly using opioid medications and similar medicines used in the "RED" category also. Green patients are fully compliant with their treatment plans and do not have aberrant results on urine drug testing and/or pill counts. Spondylosis without myelopathy or radiculopathy, lumbar region (ICD-10 - M47.816)

td.paragraph: The patient has a diagnosis of low back pain and spondylosis which has been unresponsive to conservative therapy including physical therapy, over-the-counter medications including anti-inflammatories and topical medications in addition to a home exercise program. I believe a lumbar brace is medically necessary for stabilization, pain control, postural correction and healing.

The LSO was custom fit by the physician. The brace was assembled with anterior, posterior and lateral panels and the belt was custom fit to the patient. The anterior panel was removed and heat molded. The posterior panel was removed, heat molded to patient's anatomy and contour to create intimate fit for individual lordosis of 35-45 degrees to improve proper stabilization and fit around the patient's breast tissue.
Please see accompanying documentation worksheet for details of fitting.

The patient was instructed on the proper use of the brace (ie independent compression mechanics, donning and doffing, proper angulation to ensure circumferential contact, proper placement of brace, proper cleaning and follow up appointment).

td.paragraph: To be scheduled; CMS Review: reviewed or summarized old records; Risk: minimal

Prescribing: I am prescribing an LSO (L0637) to restrict trunk movement, facilitate healing and to reduce pain. The brace should be worn during activities of daily living to increase patients function.This brace will produce intracavity pressure to reduce load on intervertebral discs, includes straps. Prefabricated item will be trimmed, bent, and molded for a customized fit for a specific patient by an individual with expertise. Patient having disabling non-radicular pain suggestive of facet joint origin as documented with mainly axial pain and physical with positive provocative signs of facet disease with pain exacerbated by extension and rotation. There is overall lack of sacroiliac joint or disc herniation causing this axial /non-radicular pain. The pain is continuous with average levels greater than or equal to 6 on a scale of 0 to 10. The duration of pain has been for longer than 6 months. The patient has also failed conservative non-operative therapy that includes a multi modality approach consisting of rest, ice, heat and modified activities and medications of NSAIDS. Patient has also failed physician supervised home exercise program SINCE 1.4.23 that included 40 minutes sessions 4x/week over the last 6 weeks without significant improvement. I believe fluoroscopy guided diagnostic Bilateral L4-5 and L5-S1 facet Medial Branch Block injection is warranted.
Bil L4/5 + L5/S1 MBB/FJI #2/2

tr.td: Spondylosis without myelopathy or radiculopathy, lumbar region (ICD-10 - M47.816)

td.paragraph: Lumbar diagnostic facet injections gave complete abolition of pain for about 6 hrs , and then 80% relief for the following 2 days.

Patient has also engaged in conservative management to include ice, heat and rest without any significant improvement. The patient should have Lumbar radiofrequency neurolysis (denervation) as the patient has pain suggestive of facet joint origin as the pain is axial and non-radicular. It was also responsive with at least 80% pain relief and 80% improved ability to perform prior painful movements without significant pain after controlled facet joint block. There is also lack of evidence that the primary source of pain is discogenic pain, sacroiliac joint pain, disc herniation or radiculitis for this particular pain. Patient has ongoing pain despite rest/ice/heat modified activities and medications. Patient has been performing SINCE 1.4.23 and will continue while in our care active home exercise program 40 minutes sessions 3x/week over the last 6 weeks that has also not been helpful.
BILATERAL L4-5 and L5-S1 radiofrequency neurolysis (denervation)

Patient having disabling non-radicular pain suggestive of facet joint origin as documented with mainly axial pain and physical with positive provocative signs of facet disease with pain exacerbated by extension and rotation. There is overall lack of sacroiliac joint or disc herniation causing this axial /non-radicular pain. The pain is continuous with average levels greater than or equal to 6 on a scale of 0 to 10. The duration of pain has been for longer than 6 months. The patient has also failed conservative non-operative therapy that includes a multi modality approach consisting of rest, ice, heat and modified activities and medications of NSAIDS. Patient has also failed physician supervised home exercise program SINCE 1.4.23 that included 40 minutes sessions 4x/week over the last 6 weeks without significant improvement. I believe fluoroscopy guided diagnostic Bilateral L4-5 and L5-S1 facet Medial Branch Block injection is warranted.
